'''''Palaeoaplysina''''' is a genus of tabular, calcified fossils that are a component of many Late Palaeozoic reefs.<ref name="Anderson_Ellesmere">{{Cite conference |year = 2011 |url = http://www.cseg.ca/conventions/abstracts/2011/259-Development_of_a_Palaeoaplysina_Reef_Complex.pdf |title = Development of a ''Palaeoaplysina'' Reef Complex, Ellesmere Island, Canadian Arctic |author1= K. D. Anderson |author2 = B. Beauchamp |conference=Recovery – 2011 CSPG CSEG CWLS Convention 1}}</ref>  The fossil acted as a baffle to trap sediment. Historically interpreted as a sponge or hydrozoan,<ref name="Davies1973">{{Cite journal | jstor = 1302890 | last1 = Davies | first1 = G. R. | last2 = Nassichuk | first2 = W. W. | title = The Hydrozoan? Palaeoaplysina from the Upper Paleozoic of Ellesmere Island, Arctic Canada | journal = Journal of Paleontology | volume = 47 | issue = 2 | pages = 251–265 | year = 1973 | doi=}}</ref> recent studies are converging to its classification in the [[coralline alga|coralline]] stem group, placing it among the [[red alga]]e.<ref name="Anderson_Ellesmere"/>

== Morphology ==

The thalloid organism had a series of internal canals opening on one side of the body (presumably the upper side), and volcano-like protuberances on that same side inviting comparison to filter-feeding organisms.  On the other hand, it seems to have had a calcified cellular make up akin to that of the coralline reds, suggesting that it was either a stem-group coralline or a coralline-encrusted filter feeder.<ref name="Anderson_GeoCanada">{{Cite conference
| url = http://www.geocanada2010.ca/program/program-schedule/posters.html
| title = The Origin and Ecology of Late Paleozoic ''Palaeoaplysina'' in Arctic Canada: An Aberrant Ancestral Coralline Algae (?) that Grew at a Time of High Atmospheric {{CO2}}
| author = Kaylee Anderson, Benoit Beauchamp
| conference = GeoCanada
| year = 2010
}}</ref>

== Distribution ==
The organism is widespread in the tropical and near-tropical margin of the Laurentian continent (45–15°N), but is not found elsewhere.<ref name="Vachard2007">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.geobios.2007.01.006 | last1 = Vachard | first1 = D. | last2 = Kabanov | first2 = P. | title = Palaeoaplysinella gen. Nov. And Likinia Ivanova and Ilkhovskii, 1973 emend., from the type Moscovian (Russia) and the algal affinities of the ancestral palaeoaplysinaceae n. Comb | journal = Geobios | volume = 40 | issue = 6 | pages = 849–860 | year = 2007 }}</ref> Its oldest reported occurrence is Middle Pennsylvanian (mid- to late Moscovian)<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ritter|first1=Scott M.|last2=Morris|first2=Thomas H.|title=Oldest and Lowest Latitudinal Occurrence of Palaeoaplysina: Middle Pennsylvanian Ely Limestone, Burbank Hills, Utah|journal=Palaios|date=August 1997|volume=12|issue=4|page=397|doi=10.2307/3515339|url=http://palaios.geoscienceworld.org/content/12/4/397.abstract?ijkey=f53b94d37008daac73e9021ae3cdee854d54d284&keytype2=tf_ipsecsha&cited-by=yes&legid=palaios;12/4/397#cited-by|accessdate=11 November 2014|jstor=3515339}}</ref> and youngest is the late Sakmarian.<ref name="Anderson_GeoCanada"/> It acts as an important reservoir rock for oil deposits.<ref name="Anderson_GeoCanada"/>

